
storage/StorageService.java
Why a dedicated storage package: File I/O is infrastructure, not business logic. AppService should not know where files live on disk.
Methods:
store(MultipartFile file, Long appId, String versionTag) → String
Returns the relative file path stored in DB. Never store absolute paths — if you move the server, all paths break.
Why these parameters: path structure should be /{appId}/{versionTag}/filename.apk. Organized by app and version so cleanup is trivial — delete the folder, all versions gone.
Internally does:

Validate file is not empty
Validate extension is .apk via StorageConfig.allowedExtensions
Validate size does not exceed StorageConfig.maxFileSizeMb
Sanitize filename — strip path traversal characters (../, /)
Generate unique filename — UUID + original_filename prevents collisions and overwrites
Create directory structure if needed
Write file to disk via Files.copy()
Return relative path

delete(String filePath) → void

Takes the stored relative path
Resolves against baseUploadPath
Deletes file, logs warning if file not found (don't throw — DB record might still need cleanup)

getAbsolutePath(String relativePath) → Path

Resolves relative path against base path
Used by download/stream endpoints later

validateFile(MultipartFile file) → void (private)

Extension check
Size check
Null/empty check
Throws InvalidFileException if any check fails


exception/InvalidFileException.java
Why: You already have InvalidOperationException but file validation failures are a distinct category. Clients need to know "your file is wrong" vs "your operation is invalid". Maps to 400.
Add handler in GlobalExceptionHandler:

Catches InvalidFileException → returns 400 with message


exception/StorageException.java
Why: Disk I/O failures are server-side, not client errors. Maps to 500. Separate from InvalidFileException so the caller knows whether to return 400 or 500.
Add handler in GlobalExceptionHandler:

Catches StorageException → returns 500 with generic message, logs full exception


dto/request/UploadVersionRequest.java
Why not just MultipartFile: Version upload needs metadata alongside the file. versionTag must come with the APK. Using a DTO alongside @RequestPart in multipart requests keeps it clean.
Fields:

String versionTag — @NotBlank @Size(max=50)
No appId here — comes from path variable, not request body


dto/response/UploadResponse.java
Why separate from AppVersionResponse: Upload response is immediate confirmation with minimal data. AppVersionResponse is for listing. Different shapes for different purposes.
Fields:

Long versionId
String versionTag
Long sizeBytes
Instant uploadedAt
String message — "APK uploaded successfully"


